### CRIT-02

**Severity:** 🔴 CRITICAL
**Title:** SSH daemon listening on `0.0.0.0:22` and `[::]:22` (all interfaces, globally reachable)

**Description:**
The SSH daemon binds to all interfaces without restriction. This means port 22 is reachable from the LAN (192.168.0.0/24) directly, from the WireGuard tunnel (10.8.0.0/24), and — depending on router NAT configuration — potentially from the internet. UFW has the following rules for SSH:

```
22                         ALLOW IN    192.168.0.0/24
22/tcp                     ALLOW IN    Anywhere          # <-- allows all IPv4
22 (v6)                    ALLOW IN    Anywhere (v6)     # <-- allows all IPv6
22 on wg0                  ALLOW IN    Anywhere
2222/tcp                   ALLOW IN    Anywhere          # <-- non-standard port, also open
2222/tcp (v6)              ALLOW IN    Anywhere (v6)
```

The `22/tcp ALLOW IN Anywhere` rule negates the VPN-restriction intent. The `2222/tcp` open rule is particularly notable — there is no service listening on 2222 in the `ss` output, suggesting this is a leftover rule from a previous configuration.

**Evidence:**
```
# ss -tlnp output
LISTEN    0    128    0.0.0.0:22    0.0.0.0:*
LISTEN    0    128       [::]:22       [::]:*
```

**Impact:**
SSH is the highest-value target on this machine. Even with fail2ban active, a globally exposed SSH port means continuous automated brute-force and credential-stuffing attempts. The `lastb` output shows 0 failed attempts — this is because the server appears to be behind NAT with no port forwarding currently. However, this is a router configuration dependency, not a server-level control. If the router config changes or the ISP assigns a routable IP, SSH becomes immediately exposed.

**Remediation:**
```bash
# 1. Restrict SSH to WireGuard interface only in sshd_config
sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config
# Add:
ListenAddress 10.8.0.1
ListenAddress 192.168.0.16
# This restricts SSH to wg0 and LAN interface only

# 2. Clean up UFW rules
sudo ufw delete allow 22/tcp             # removes the "Anywhere" rule
sudo ufw delete allow 2222/tcp           # remove unused port
sudo ufw allow in on wg0 to any port 22 proto tcp
sudo ufw allow from 192.168.0.0/24 to any port 22 proto tcp

# 3. Restart SSH
sudo systemctl restart ssh

# 4. Verify (from a separate session before closing current one)
ss -tlnp | grep :22
```

> ⚠️ **Always maintain an active session before restarting SSH. Test from a new connection before closing the current one.**

