### HIGH-02

**Severity:** 🟠 HIGH
**Title:** Apache2 running on ports 80 and 443 with no documented operational purpose

**Description:**
Apache2 is active and listening on `*:80` and `*:443`. There is also a `certbot` cron entry and a `certbot.timer` active in systemd, indicating TLS certificates are being maintained. The running services also include a `check-nextcloud.timer` and a `nextcloud-backup.sh` cron entry. This suggests Nextcloud may have been installed at some point but is not confirmed running as a service.

**Evidence:**
```
apache2.service   loaded active running   The Apache HTTP Server
# ss output
LISTEN    0    511    *:80     *:*
LISTEN    0    511    *:443    *:*
# timers
certbot.timer — active
check-nextcloud.timer — active
```

**Impact:**
An Apache2 instance with no maintained application is a significant attack surface. Default configurations, unpatched modules, or leftover web applications (Nextcloud, phpMyAdmin, etc.) are common vectors for initial access. Port 80/443 are the most commonly scanned ports on the internet. If the server has any form of public reachability (direct IP or through a DDNS entry like `ipshadow.ddns.net`), this is externally exposed.

**Remediation — Option A (Nextcloud is still needed):**
```bash
# Verify what's actually served
sudo apache2ctl -S
ls /etc/apache2/sites-enabled/
curl -sk https://localhost/ | head -20

# If Nextcloud is operational, ensure:
# - It is updated to latest version
# - Access is restricted to VPN/LAN via Apache config or UFW
# - UFW blocks 80/443 from internet (only allow from 10.8.0.0/24 or 192.168.0.0/24)
sudo ufw allow from 10.8.0.0/24 to any port 443 proto tcp
sudo ufw allow from 192.168.0.0/24 to any port 443 proto tcp
```

**Remediation — Option B (Apache/Nextcloud not needed):**
```bash
sudo systemctl stop apache2
sudo systemctl disable apache2
sudo systemctl stop certbot.timer
sudo systemctl disable certbot.timer
# Review and disable check-nextcloud.timer
sudo systemctl stop check-nextcloud.timer
sudo systemctl disable check-nextcloud.timer
```

