### MED-04

**Severity:** 🟡 MEDIUM
**Title:** UFW ruleset contains redundant, conflicting, and imprecise entries

**Description:**
The UFW ruleset has accumulated rules that conflict with the intended security model. Key issues:

1. `22/tcp ALLOW IN Anywhere` — overrides the intent to restrict SSH to VPN/LAN
2. `2222/tcp ALLOW IN Anywhere` — no service is listening on 2222; orphaned rule
3. `3389/tcp ALLOW IN 192.168.0.0` — uses network address instead of `/24` subnet notation
4. `Anywhere ALLOW IN 10.8.0.0/24` — allows ALL traffic from WireGuard peers, including to Samba, MariaDB-adjacent ports, etc. This is a broad allow that should be reviewed per-service.

**Evidence:**
```
# UFW status output (abbreviated):
22/tcp           ALLOW IN    Anywhere
2222/tcp         ALLOW IN    Anywhere
3389/tcp         ALLOW IN    192.168.0.0     # should be 192.168.0.0/24
Anywhere         ALLOW IN    10.8.0.0/24    # too broad
```

**Remediation:**
```bash
# Full UFW cleanup — recommended rule set:
sudo ufw --force reset

# Core rules
sudo ufw default deny incoming
sudo ufw default allow outgoing
sudo ufw default deny routed

# WireGuard port (must be first — required to establish VPN)
sudo ufw allow 51820/udp

# SSH: WireGuard tunnel only + LAN
sudo ufw allow in on wg0 to any port 22 proto tcp
sudo ufw allow from 192.168.0.0/24 to any port 22 proto tcp

# RDP: WireGuard tunnel only
sudo ufw allow in on wg0 to any port 3389 proto tcp

# Samba: WireGuard tunnel + LAN only
sudo ufw allow in on wg0 to any port 445 proto tcp
sudo ufw allow from 192.168.0.0/24 to any port 445 proto tcp

# HTTP/HTTPS (only if Apache/Nextcloud is intentionally running):
# sudo ufw allow in on wg0 to any port 443 proto tcp
# sudo ufw allow from 192.168.0.0/24 to any port 443 proto tcp

sudo ufw enable
sudo ufw status verbose
```

> ⚠️ Always verify SSH access from a second terminal before closing the current session after UFW changes.

